    <body.head>
      <hedline>
        <hl1>Are National ID's an Invitation to Abuse?</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Christopher F Miller letter holds trouble with Nicholas Kristof's proposal for national ID card (March 17 column) is that it would turn every cash register, business, bus station and voting booth into a checkpoint</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>The problem with having a national ID, which Nicholas D. Kristof proposes (column, March 17), is not the ID itself, but how it would turn every cash register, business, bus station and voting booth into a checkpoint -- and not just of you, but of all your associations and movements.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>The problem with having a national ID, which Nicholas D. Kristof proposes (column, March 17), is not the ID itself, but how it would turn every cash register, business, bus station and voting booth into a checkpoint -- and not just of you, but of all your associations and movements.</p>
        <p>Compared with this, Afghanistan under the Taliban would look sweet.</p>
        <p>CHRISTOPHER F. MILLER  Gray, Me., March 17, 2004</p>
      </block>
    </body.content>
